Module 1 — Introduction to Excel

Understanding the basics of Microsoft Excel

What is Excel?

Microsoft Excel is a spreadsheet tool used for data entry, analysis, and reporting. It helps teams organize information, perform calculations, visualize insights, and collaborate efficiently.

Tip: Think of Excel as a digital notebook—each worksheet is a page; each page is made of tiny boxes (cells).

Interface Overview

  • Ribbon: Tabs like Home, Insert, Formulas, Data, Review
  • Workbook: The entire file (e.g., SalesReport.xlsx)
  • Worksheet: Individual sheets within a workbook
  • Cell: Intersection of row & column (e.g., A1)
  • Name Box & Formula Bar: Shows active cell and the formula/content
  • Status Bar: Quick stats (Sum/Avg/Count) for selected cells

Workbook vs Worksheet

Workbook = File (contains one or more sheets)

Worksheets = Tabs inside the workbook (e.g., Data, Analysis, Dashboard)

Cells & Ranges

  • Cell: A1, B5, C10
  • Range: A1:A10, A1:C10
  • Active Cell: Currently selected cell
  • Selection: Click-drag or Shift+Arrow
Keyboard Shortcuts
Ctrl+S (Save)
Ctrl+C/V (Copy/Paste)
Ctrl+Z (Undo)
Ctrl+Arrow (Jump across data)
Ctrl+PgUp/PgDn (Switch sheets)

Saving Files

  • Local: File → Save As → This PC
  • Cloud: OneDrive or SharePoint for co-authoring
  • Formats: .xlsx (standard), .xlsm (macros), .xlsb (binary), .csv (plain data)

Mini Exercise

Open Excel and create a new workbook.
Rename Sheet1 to Practice.
Enter sample data: Name, Age, City.
Save the file to OneDrive and close.

Module 2 — Data Entry & Formatting

Input data effectively and format it for professional presentation

Types of Data

  • Text: Names, labels, categories
  • Numbers: Quantities, IDs, amounts
  • Dates & Times: Scheduling, logs, timelines
  • Formulas: Expressions that calculate results (e.g., =SUM(A1:A10))

Entering Data

  • Click a cell and type directly
  • Use Tab to move across a row, Enter to move down
  • Double-click cell borders to auto-fit content
  • Copy (Ctrl+C) and Paste (Ctrl+V) for efficiency

Formatting Essentials

  • Fonts & Alignment: Bold headers, centered titles
  • Borders & Shading: Group related data
  • Number Formats: Currency (₹), Percentage (%), Date
  • Cell Styles: Apply predefined themes for consistency

Conditional Formatting

Highlight key insights automatically, e.g.:

  • Sales < 1000 → Red fill
  • Top 10% performers → Green highlight
  • Duplicate entries → Light yellow
Tip: Good formatting isn’t decoration—it makes your spreadsheet easier to read and reduces errors.

Data Validation

  • Restrict inputs (e.g., allow only whole numbers between 1 and 100)
  • Create drop-down lists for consistent categories
  • Show error messages for invalid entries

Mini Exercise

Enter a small dataset (Name, Age, Department, Salary).
Apply bold + border to headers, align text properly.
Format Salary as Currency (₹).
Apply conditional formatting: highlight ages above 40.
Add data validation drop-down for Department (HR, Finance, Sales).

Module 3 — Basic Formulas

Understanding how to calculate and analyze with formulas

What is a Formula?

A formula is an instruction to Excel to perform a calculation. Every formula starts with an = (equal sign).

  • Numbers: =10+5
  • Cell references: =A1+B1
  • Built-in functions: =SUM(A1:A5)

Trainer Demo: Type =2+3 in a cell → Excel returns 5.

Cell References

  • Relative (A1): Adjusts when copied.
  • Absolute ($A$1): Fixed, does not change.
  • Mixed (A$1 or $A1): Either row or column fixed.

SUM and AVERAGE

  • =SUM(A1:A10) → Adds up values in the range
  • =AVERAGE(B1:B10) → Calculates the mean

MIN and MAX

  • =MIN(C1:C20) → Smallest value
  • =MAX(C1:C20) → Largest value

COUNT and COUNTA

  • =COUNT(D1:D20) → Counts only numbers
  • =COUNTA(D1:D20) → Counts numbers + text

IF and COUNTIF

  • =IF(E1>=50,"Pass","Fail") → Conditional check
  • =COUNTIF(F1:F20,"HR") → Counts cells that match criteria

Mini Exercise

Create a table with Product, Quantity, Price.
Insert a column Total = Quantity × Price.
Use SUM to calculate the grand total.
Apply AVERAGE, MIN, and MAX on totals.
Use IF to classify totals as "High" or "Low".

Module 4 — Intermediate Formulas

Text, Date, Lookup, and Error Handling

Text Functions (Cleaning & Formatting)

  • =TRIM(text) → Removes extra spaces
  • =CLEAN(text) → Removes non-printable characters
  • =PROPER(text) → Capitalizes first letter of each word
  • =UPPER(text) → Converts to uppercase
  • =LOWER(text) → Converts to lowercase

Text Functions (Splitting & Joining)

  • =LEFT(text,num_chars) → Extracts characters from start
  • =RIGHT(text,num_chars) → Extracts characters from end
  • =LEN(text) → Returns length of string
  • =CONCAT(A1,B1) → Joins text values
  • =TEXTJOIN(" ",TRUE,A1:B1) → Joins text with delimiter

Date Functions

  • =TODAY() → Current date
  • =NOW() → Current date & time
  • =DATEDIF(start,end,"Y") → Difference in years
  • =EOMONTH(start,0) → End of month date
  • =DAY(), =MONTH(), =YEAR() → Extract date parts

Lookup Functions

Lookup functions help you search for a value in a range and return related information.

  • =VLOOKUP(lookup_value, table_array, col_index_num, [range_lookup])
  • =INDEX(array, row_num, [col_num])
  • =MATCH(lookup_value, lookup_array, [match_type])
  • =XLOOKUP(lookup_value, lookup_array, return_array) → Modern replacement for VLOOKUP

Error Handling

  • =IFERROR(value, value_if_error) → Replace errors with a custom result
  • =IFNA(value, value_if_na) → Handle #N/A errors specifically

Mini Exercise

Use PROPER to clean up names entered in mixed case.
Extract birth year from a column of dates using =YEAR().
Apply VLOOKUP to find employee salary based on ID.
Wrap formulas with IFERROR to avoid #N/A outputs.

Module 5 — Advanced Formulas

Nested logic, dynamic arrays, and advanced referencing

Nested IF & IFS

Build multi-condition logic using nested IF, or use IFS for cleaner rules.

  • Nested IF (pattern): =IF(cond1,res1, IF(cond2,res2, "Default"))
  • IFS (Excel 2016+): =IFS(A2>=90,"A", A2>=75,"B", A2>=50,"C", A2<50,"F")

Use IFS to avoid deeply nested parentheses and improve readability.

Dynamic Array Functions (Microsoft 365+)

  • =FILTER(array, include) → Return rows that meet a condition
  • =UNIQUE(array) → Distinct values
  • =SORT(array, [sort_index], [order]) → Sort results
  • =SEQUENCE(rows, [columns], [start], [step]) → Generate sequential numbers

Dynamic arrays “spill” results to neighboring cells automatically.

Advanced Referencing

  • INDIRECT: Build a reference from text → =INDIRECT("Sheet2!B2")
  • OFFSET: Move from a starting cell by rows/cols → =OFFSET(A1,2,1) (2 down, 1 right)

Pair with dropdowns or helper cells to make references dynamic.

Error Handling

  • =IFERROR(value, value_if_error) → Replace any error with a friendly message/value
  • =IFNA(value, value_if_na) → Specifically handle #N/A
Combo Example (Average for a product, with fallback)
=IFERROR(AVERAGE(FILTER(C2:C100, A2:A100="Pen")), "No Data")
Returns the average sales for “Pen”, or “No Data” if no rows match.

Sample Patterns

  • Unique products: =UNIQUE(A2:A500)
  • Filter by product: =FILTER(C2:C500, A2:A500="Pen")
  • Sort by sales (desc): =SORT(A2:C500, 3, -1)
  • Dynamic pick (2 down, 1 right of A1): =OFFSET(A1,2,1)

Mini Exercise

Assign grades using Nested IF or IFS.
List all distinct cities with UNIQUE and then SORT them.
Use FILTER to return only sales for “Pen”.
Use OFFSET to return a value 2 rows down and 1 column right from a start cell.
Combine IFERROR + AVERAGE + FILTER to compute average sales with a safe fallback.

Module 6 — Data Cleaning & Preparing Datasets

From messy raw data to structured, analysis-ready data

Why Data Cleaning Matters

  • Real-world data is messy: extra spaces, inconsistent formats
  • Blank rows/columns and merged cells cause formula/chart issues
  • Duplicates skew analysis

Trainer note: “Garbage in = Garbage out.” Clean data → accurate formulas, charts, pivots.

Dataset Best Practices

  • Single header row only
  • No merged cells
  • Remove blank rows/columns
  • Consistent data types (numbers as numbers, dates as dates)
  • Use an Excel Table for structure and filters

Quick Clean-Up (Worksheet)

  • TRIM / CLEAN / PROPER to fix text
  • Remove Duplicates (Data → Remove Duplicates)
  • Text to Columns for splitting names/codes
  • Find & Replace to fix common patterns
  • Data Validation to restrict/standardize entries

Power Query (Get & Transform)

  • Import from Excel/CSV/Folder
  • Remove duplicates, split columns, change types
  • Promote headers, unpivot, merge/append queries
  • Refresh to reapply all cleaning steps

Power Query creates a repeatable cleaning pipeline—great for monthly files.

Common Fix Set
=TRIM(CLEAN(A2)) → strip extra spaces & non-printables
Use Data → Remove Duplicates, then validate with filters.

Mini Exercise

Convert raw list to an Excel Table.
Fix names with =PROPER(TRIM(CLEAN()))).
Remove duplicate rows.
Split “Full Name” into First/Last via Text to Columns.
Apply Data Validation for Region (HR/Finance/Sales etc.).

Power Query Exercise

Load the same data into Power Query.
Apply steps: Remove Duplicates → Split Column → Change Type.
Close & Load as a new table; click Refresh to repeat.

Module 7 — Preparing Datasets for Analysis

Structuring, linking, and sharing data

What Makes a Good Dataset?

  • Clear headers (Row 1 only)
  • No merged cells
  • Consistent data types (numbers, dates, text)
  • Each row = one record; each column = one field

Convert Range into Table

Why Tables? Auto-expand, structured references, easy filters & styles.

Select the dataset → press Ctrl + T.
Confirm “My table has headers”.
Name it (Table Design → Table Name).
Use structured refs in formulas (e.g., =SUM(Table1[Sales])).

Named Ranges

  • Create names via Formulas → Name Manager
  • Use in formulas: =SUM(SalesAmount)
  • Keep names short, clear, and scoped appropriately

Linking Across Sheets & Workbooks

  • Same workbook: =Sheet2!B2
  • Another workbook: ='[SalesData.xlsx]Jan'!$C$5
  • Prefer stable structure (tables/named ranges) before linking
  • Document links for maintainability
OneDrive/SharePoint Sharing
Save to OneDrive/SharePoint → use Share to control access and enable co-authoring.

Good vs Bad Dataset (Checklist)

  • Bad: Merged headers, blank rows, subtotals mixed with data
  • Good: Flat table: Product | Region | Date | Sales
  • Keep calculations out of the raw table (use separate summary)

Mini Exercise

Fix a “Bad” dataset: remove blanks, unmerge, standardize headers.
Convert the cleaned range to an Excel Table and name it.
Create a named range for SalesAmount and use it in a SUM.
Link a summary sheet to your table using structured references.
Optionally, link to another workbook and observe the reference path.

Module 8 — Tables & Charts

Turning datasets into visual insights

Why Use Tables & Charts?

Tables: Organize, format, and filter data.

Charts: Transform raw numbers into clear visuals.

  • Easier analysis
  • Faster decision-making
  • Engaging presentations

Creating Excel Tables

Select dataset → press Ctrl + T.
Check “My table has headers”.
Apply Table Styles (Design tab).
Use filter arrows to sort/filter data.

Tables auto-expand when you add new rows.

Table Features

  • Auto-expanding formulas (e.g., =SUM(SalesTable[Sales]))
  • Built-in formatting styles
  • Easy filtering by headers
  • Structured references instead of A1:B2

Chart Types

  • Column & Bar → Compare values
  • Line → Show trends over time
  • Pie & Donut → Show proportions
  • Combo Chart → Dual-axis comparisons

Tip: Choose chart type based on the story you want to tell.

Dynamic Charts
Use =OFFSET() to define dynamic ranges for charts, or simply use Tables in Excel 365 (auto-expands).

Creating a Chart

Select dataset (or Table).
Go to Insert → Chart Type.
Format chart (titles, labels, legends, colors).

Examples: Sales by Product → Column Chart | Monthly Sales → Line Chart

Mini Exercise

Convert dataset into a Table.
Insert a Column Chart (Sales by Product).
Insert a Line Chart (Sales by Date).
Format with titles, colors, and data labels.
Add new data → Watch Table & Chart auto-update.

Module 9 — Pivot Tables & Pivot Charts

Summarize and analyze data instantly

What is a Pivot Table?

A Pivot Table is Excel’s most powerful summary tool. It lets you reorganize (“pivot”) data to answer key questions:

  • Total Sales by Region
  • Average Sales per Product
  • Monthly Trends

No formulas needed — drag & drop fields into areas.

Creating a Pivot Table

Select dataset → Insert → PivotTable.
Place Pivot Table in a new or existing sheet.
Drag fields into:
  • Rows → Categories (Product, Region)
  • Columns → Subcategories (Months)
  • Values → Metrics (Sum of Sales)
  • Filters → Slice data (Year)

Pivot Table Features

  • Grouping: Dates (Month/Quarter/Year), Numbers (0–500, 500–1000)
  • Sorting & Filtering
  • Calculated Fields → Custom formulas
  • Show % of Total (e.g., Product as % of All Sales)

Pivot Charts

  • Visual linked to a Pivot Table (Column, Bar, Line, Pie)
  • Interactive with Filters, Slicers, Timelines

Example: Sales by Region (Pivot Table) → Column Pivot Chart.

Slicers & Timelines
  • Slicers: Clickable buttons to filter (e.g., by Region)
  • Timeline: Interactive slider to filter by Date
Great for interactive dashboards.

Common Use Cases

  • Sales Analysis (Product, Region, Time)
  • Financial Reports (Income vs Expenses)
  • HR Reports (Headcount, Attrition)
  • Customer Analysis (Orders by Segment)

Mini Exercise

Create a Pivot Table → Sales by Product.
Add Region as Columns → Product × Region sales.
Group Dates by Month → Monthly Sales trend.
Insert Pivot Chart (Column).
Add Slicer (Region) and Timeline (Date).

Module 10 — Dynamic Dashboards

Creating interactive reports in Excel

What is a Dashboard?

A Dashboard is a visual summary of key metrics that combines charts, tables, slicers, and KPIs.

Think of it like a car dashboard → quick overview, not raw details.

  • Clear KPIs (Sales, Profit, Growth)
  • Minimal clutter
  • Interactive filters
  • Consistent colors and fonts

Building a Dashboard — Step by Step

Prepare dataset (clean, structured, Table format).
Insert Pivot Tables (summaries by Product, Region, Month).
Add Pivot Charts (Column, Line, Pie).
Insert Slicers/Timelines for interactivity.
Arrange in a grid-based Dashboard sheet.
Format & polish with titles, colors, and KPIs.

Example Layout

  • Top row: KPIs (Total Sales, Avg Sales, Highest Sale)
  • Left panel: Slicers (Region, Product)
  • Center: Charts (Sales Trend, Sales by Product)
  • Right panel: Table (Top 5 Products)

KPIs with Formulas

  • Total Sales → =SUM(SalesTable[Sales])
  • Average Monthly Sales → =AVERAGE(SalesTable[Sales])
  • Highest Sale → =MAX(SalesTable[Sales])

Format as KPI cards with bold fonts, large numbers, and icons (🔼 / 🔽).

Interactivity
  • Slicers → Filter by Product, Region
  • Timelines → Filter by Date (Year, Quarter, Month)
Link slicers/timelines to multiple Pivot Tables for synced filtering.

Designing for Impact

  • Use company theme colors
  • Place KPIs at the top
  • Minimize gridlines/clutter
  • Highlight changes with icons or conditional formatting

Mini Exercise

Create a Pivot Table: Sales by Product.
Insert Pivot Charts: Sales Trend by Month, Sales by Region.
Add Slicer (Product, Region) and Timeline (Date).
Create KPIs (Total, Avg, Max Sales).
Arrange into a grid-based dashboard layout.

Module 11 — Collaboration & Sharing

OneDrive, SharePoint, and protecting data

Why Collaboration Matters

  • Work together on the same file in real-time
  • Share dashboards with managers, datasets with analysts
  • Track edits with version history
  • Protect sensitive sheets and formulas

Excel is no longer a solo tool — cloud integration makes it collaborative.

Saving to Cloud

File → Save As → Choose OneDrive/SharePoint.
Select folder → Save → Auto-sync enabled.

Local saves = private. Cloud saves = collaborative.

Sharing Files

  • File → Share → Enter emails or copy link
  • Permissions:
    • ✅ Can View → Read-only
    • ✅ Can Edit → Collaborative editing
  • Use “View only” for dashboards, “Edit” for datasets

Co-Authoring in Real-Time

  • Multiple users editing = instant sync
  • Colored cursors highlight each user
  • Auto-save is always ON in cloud files

Trainer demo: Show two people typing in same Excel file via OneDrive.

Version History
File → Info → Version History → Restore/compare older versions.
Ideal for audit trails and mistake recovery.

Protecting Data

  • Protect Sheet: Lock worksheet to prevent accidental edits
  • Protect Workbook: Stop adding/deleting sheets
  • Cell-Level Protection: Lock formulas, leave input cells open
  • Advanced (Enterprise): Restrict downloads, set expiry, require sign-in

Mini Exercise

Save a file to OneDrive.
Share with teammate (View only).
Enable co-authoring (Edit access).
Protect worksheet: lock formulas, keep input open.
Restore a file version via Version History.

Module 12 — Final Project & File Types

Applying all skills + Understanding file extensions

Final Project Overview

The capstone pulls everything together into a real-world Excel workflow:

  • Data Cleaning & Preparation
  • Structuring dataset as a Table
  • Formulas (basic → advanced)
  • Pivot Tables & Charts
  • Dynamic Dashboard with KPIs & Slicers
  • Sharing via OneDrive/SharePoint
  • Protecting sensitive data

Project Tasks

Step 1: Clean raw data (remove duplicates, blanks, merged cells; fix names/dates).
Step 2: Convert into a Table (Ctrl+T) → Name: SalesData.
Step 3: Add formulas (e.g., Profit Margin, Category with IF).
Step 4: Build Pivot Tables (by Product, Region, Month).
Step 5: Create Charts (Column, Line, Pie).
Step 6: Assemble Dashboard (KPIs, slicers, timeline, clean layout).
Step 7: Save to OneDrive, share, protect sheets.

Project Deliverables

  • Cleaned dataset in Table format
  • 3 Pivot Tables + Pivot Charts
  • Dynamic Dashboard with KPIs
  • Protected Sheet (input only editable)
  • Shared via OneDrive (View/Edit links)

Excel File Extensions

  • .xlsx → Default, formulas/charts, no macros
  • .xlsm → Macro-enabled
  • .xlsb → Binary, faster for large datasets
  • .xls → Legacy (Excel 97–2003)
  • .csv → Plain-text, data exchange, no formatting
  • .xltx / .xltm → Templates (with/without macros)

Tip: Use .xlsx for daily work, .xlsm for macros, .xlsb for big files, .csv for exchange with ERP/SQL/Python/R.

Mini Capstone Exercise
  • Clean Sales dataset → Convert to Table (SalesData).
  • Create Pivot: Sales by Product + Monthly Trend.
  • Build Dashboard: KPIs, charts, slicer, timeline.
  • Protect formulas, share via OneDrive.
  • Save in .xlsx, .xlsb, .csv → Explain differences.
